            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Although this refusal to drink the wine, which is not to be explained away, is ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "in itself",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " psychologically conceivable in so deeply moved and painful a state of mind, yet it is improbable in consideration of the characteristic element of the Passover. In respect of this, the drinking of the Passover wine was certainly so essential, and, in the consciousness of the person celebrating the rite, so necessary, that the not drinking, and especially on the part of the Host Himself, would have appeared absolutely as contrary to the law, irreligious, scandalous, an interruption which, on the part of Jesus, can hardly be credible. Since then Mark and Matthew, moreover, have nothing at all about a refusal of the wine, but rather do not bring in the assurance, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "οὐ μὴ πίω κ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "τ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "λ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "., until the conclusion of the meal, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Mark 14:25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 26:29",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; and since Matthew uses the emphatic ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἀπʼ ἄρτι",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", wherein is intimated that Jesus had just drunk with them once more,—the narrative of Luke, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 22:17-18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", is to be regarded as not original, and it is to be assumed that Jesus indeed spoke, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 22:15-16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", at the beginning of the meal (in opposition to Kuinoel and Paulus), but that what is found in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 26:29",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " has been removed back by the tradition on account of the analogy of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 22:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and placed after ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 22:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", beside which ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 22:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " easily appeared as a link, without the necessity of attributing to Luke the construction of a piece of mosaic from a twofold source (as Holtzmann wishes to do), especially as ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 22:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is not yet the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "cup of the Lord’s Supper",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". According to Baur, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Evang",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". p. 482 f., Luke must have been led by 1 Corinthians 10, where, moreover, the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ποτήριον τῆς εὐλογίας",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is emphatically placed first, to distinguish two acts in the Lord’s Supper (comp. also Ritschl, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Evang. Marcion’s",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", p. 108), one with the leading idea of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "κοινωνία",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and the other with that of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἀνάμνησις",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". He must have here represented the first by the help of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 26:29",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". He must thus probably still have expressly brought in the supposed leading idea of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "κοινωνία",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", as Paul also has done in respect of the bread. In general, the use made by Luke of the Pauline ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Epistles",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", which here even Hilgenfeld (comp. Holtzmann, p. 237) considers as unmistakeable, is quite incapable of proof.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
